[[File:Metroon del Agora de Atenas.JPG|thumb|The Metroon in Athens.]] A '''metroon''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Μητρῷον}}, ''Mētrō̂on'' or ''Mētrō̂ion'') was an [[ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[greek temple|temple]] dedicated to a [[mother goddess]]. They were often devoted to [[Cybele]], [[Demeter]], or [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]].
==Athens == [[Geographic coordinate system|Coordinates]]: {{coord|37.975214|N|23.722077|E|type:landmark_region:GR_scale:500|}}
The [[classical Athens|Athenian]] Metroon was located on the west side of the city's [[Athenian Agora|Agora]], in the [[Bouleuterion#Athens|Old Bouleuterion]] which formerly housed the [[boule (ancient Greece)|city council]]. At the end of the 5th century&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}, the [[New Bouleuterion]] was built and the council's former home converted into a temple to [[Cybele]]. Supposedly, the Athenians had killed one of her wandering priests when he attempted to introduce her cult; the plague which then visited the city was dealt with by honoring her. (The account may, however, have been a later invention, as the earliest source is from the 4th century&nbsp;{{sc|ad}}.)<ref>[[Julian (emperor)|Julian]]. "Hymn to the Mother of the Gods". (362).</ref><ref>Roller, 1999. pp. 162 - 167</ref><ref>Roscoe, p. 200</ref><ref>Robertson, in Lane, p. 258.</ref> The Metroon continued to serve a public function, housing the official archives of the city.<ref>[http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/dunkle/athnlife/metroon.htm The Metrôon (Old Bouleuterion)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206100721/http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/dunkle/athnlife/metroon.htm |date=2007-02-06 }} at ''Athenian Daily Life'', [[Brooklyn College]], [[City University of New York]].</ref>
== Olympia== The [[Olympia, Greece|Olympian]] Metroon was erected in the late 4th or early 3rd century&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} immediately below the terrace which housed the [[Treasuries at Olympia|Treasuries]].<ref>[http://www.planetware.com/olympia/olympia-metroon-gr-pel-metroo.htm Olympía - Metroon]</ref>
==See also== * [[ancient Greek religion|Greek religion]] * [[Greek temple]]s * [[Synagogue in the Agora of Athens]], evidence of which was found nearby
