'''Panhu''' (盤瓠 /{{IPA|pán hù}}/) is an important dog in [[Chinese mythology]]. The Panhu mythological complex includes myths in [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and also other languages. This myth has a long history of being transmitted by [[Han Chinese]] and several of the other ethnic groups of the fifty-six officially recognized by the current administration of China, both orally and in literature.<ref>[http://202.40.204.216/etext/chi/chi305/2002_3/pdf/chi305_0304.pdf 盤瓠與民族原推圖騰神話]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://202.40.204.216/etext/chi/chi305/2002_3/pdf/chi305_0302.pdf 盤瓠 ― 民族推源圖騰]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> (Yang 2005:4) The Panhu myth is an important origin myth for various ethnic groups.
==Basic myth== The basic Panhu myth is about a dog (or dragon-dog) who transforms into a man and married a princess. The emperor of China in the course of losing a war which he was waging with a neighbor to the west, offered to marry his daughter to anybody that would present him with the head of his enemy. This was accomplished by the dog. Accounts vary, but eventually the dog and princess procreated copiously, producing many descendants.
==Variants== There are also various variant versions.<ref>[http://iel.cass.cn/news_show.asp?newsid=2045 盘瓠神话：楚与卢戎的一场战争·中国民族文学网]</ref><ref>[http://www.hmongbq.com/ReadNews.asp?NewsID=230 苗族民间祭祀制度 吴正彪]</ref><ref>[http://www.library.ln.edu.hk/etext/chi/chi305/2002_3/pdf/chi305_0304.pdf 葉曉文 盤瓠與民族原推圖騰神話]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://commons.ln.edu.hk/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&context=chin_proj_1 盤瓠神話]</ref> In some the dog became transformed into a human, except for his head. (Christie 1968: 121-122)
==Myth versus history== In the study of historical Chinese culture, many of the stories that have been told regarding characters and events which have been written or told of the distant past have a double tradition: one which tradition which presents a more historicized and one which presents a more mythological version. (Yang 2005:12-13) This is also true in many of the accounts related to the Panhu.
==Religion== Many of the myths regarding agriculture in China are related to popular religion and ritual. In modern times, Panhu has been worshipped by the [[Yao people]] and [[She people]] as "King Pan". (Yang 2005: 52-53).
