'''Robert J. Fox''' (1930 – April 27, 1984) was an associate pastor of [[St. Paul's Church (New York City)|St. Paul's Church]] in East Harlem and former coordinator of the [[Spanish Community Action]] program in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bird|first1=David|title=MSGR. ROBERT J. FOX, 54, DIES; AIDE TO HISPANIC COMMUNITY|journal=The New York Times|date=April 30, 1984|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/30/obituaries/msgr-robert-j-fox-54-dies-aide-to-hispanic-community.html|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>
==Community Work and Activism== Robert J. Fox was responsible for conceiving [[Summer in the City (city program)]], a New York City antipoverty program with efforts concentrated in the South Bronx, East Harlem, and Lower East Side.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cole|first1=Mary|title=Summer in the City|date=1968|publisher=Kennedy|location=New York}}</ref> The project was funded by the federal Office of Economic Opportunity and in 1967 ran a total of 26 storefront centers and employed 580 workers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stevenson|first1=James|title=The People All The People|journal=The New Yorker|date=September 16, 1967|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1967/09/16/the-people-all-the-people|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>
==Influence== The "spirit" of [[Summer in the City (city program)]] was influential to [[Susan Shapiro Kiok]], one of the artists in the city program.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Braun-Reinitz|first1=Janet|title=On the Wall: four decades of community murals in New York City|date=2009|publisher=The University Press of Mississippi|location=Jackson|isbn=9781604731118|page=18}}</ref> Susan went on to incorporate [[Cityarts Workshop]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite book|title=ibid|page=19}}</ref>
