'''''Shadchan''''' ({{Lang-he|שַׁדְּכָן}}, plural '''''shadchanim''''' or '''''shadchonim''''' {{Lang-he|שַׁדְּכֳנִם}}) is a [[Hebrew]] word for [[matchmaking|matchmaker]].

The word Shadchan often refers to ''Shadchanim'' or people who carry out [[Shidduchim]] as a profession within the religious Jewish community. However, Shadchan can also be used to refer to anyone who introduces two single Jews to one another with the hope that they will form a couple. Centuries of experience and tradition have shown that a good match is most likely to be formed between people with similar outlooks, attitudes, beliefs and backgrounds.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} Therefore, a matchmaker is most likely to be someone who is familiar with both sides and is in a position to introduce the interested parties to each other. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}

